# JavaScript/React Style Guide

## Variables

You must:
- Use const by default for all declarations
- Use let only when reassignment is needed
- Never use var
- Always destructure objects and arrays when accessing multiple properties

## Functions

You must:
- Use arrow functions for callbacks and anonymous functions
- Use template literals for string interpolation (backticks)

## Objects & Arrays

You must:
- Use object shorthand when property name matches variable name
- Use spread operator (...) for copying/merging objects and arrays

## React Components

You must:
- Create functional components only (no class components)
- Use named exports (export const Component) not default exports
- Destructure props in function parameters

## Hooks

You must:
- Call hooks at top level only (not inside conditions/loops)
- Name custom hooks with "use" prefix (useRecipes, useDebounce)
- Use useCallback for function memoization
- Use useMemo for expensive calculations

## JSX

You must:
- Self-close tags that have no children (<Component />)
- Omit ={true} for boolean props (<Input required />)
- Wrap multi-line JSX in parentheses
- Provide unique key prop for list items (use ID, never array index)
- Name event handler functions with handle prefix (handleClick)
- Name event handler props with on prefix (onClick, onSelect)
- Use && for conditional display: {isLoading && <Spinner />}
- Use ternary for if-else: {error ? <Error /> : <Content />}

## Naming

You must use:
- Components: PascalCase for names and files (RecipeCard.jsx)
- Functions/Variables: camelCase (handleClick, maxRetries)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (API_BASE_URL, MAX_RETRIES)
- Custom Hooks: use + camelCase (useRecipes, useDebounce)
- Booleans: is/has/should prefix (isLoading, hasError, shouldShow)

## File Organization

You must order imports:
1. React imports first
2. Third-party libraries
3. Local imports (components, hooks, utils)
